The latest MSTest is **4.2.1** (a major version jump from 3.8.0). Your `net8.0` target is supported, but there's one breaking change that **directly affects your code**:

### `[ExpectedException]` is removed in v4

Both your test methods use `[ExpectedException]`, which no longer exists. Replace with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()`:

```diff
- [ExpectedException(typeof(ArgumentNullException))]
  [TestMethod]
  public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
  {
-     Validate(null);
+     Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
  }

- [ExpectedException(typeof(InvalidOperationException))]
  [TestMethod]
  public void Process_InvalidState_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
  {
-     Process();
+     Assert.ThrowsExactly<InvalidOperationException>(() => Process());
  }
```

### Other v4 breaking changes (not hitting your code today, but good to know)

| Change | Impact |
|---|---|
| `Assert.ThrowsException` removed | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` instead |
| `Assert` message+params APIs simplified | Use string interpolation instead of `message, params object[]` |
| `ClassCleanupBehavior` enum removed | Just use `[ClassCleanup]` without the enum |
| `TestTimeout` enum removed | Use `[Timeout(int.MaxValue)]` |
| `TestContext.ManagedType` removed | Use `TestContext.FullyQualifiedTestClassName` |
| `TestContext.Properties` is now `IDictionary<string, object>` | Use `.ContainsKey()` instead of `.Contains()` |
| Custom `TestMethodAttribute.Execute` → `ExecuteAsync` | Only if you subclass `TestMethodAttribute` |
| Stricter analyzer defaults | Several analyzers now default to Warning |

